No, apparently not. The creature growled only and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Luckily, Thassalin was agile enough despite his size and dodged out of the way, but Nyssi let out a scream, as she almost lost her balance on Thassalin's smooth scales.
“HOW CAN WE KILL IT?”, screamed Nyssi.
“TARGET THEIR HEADS!”
“THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT!”
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, closer to the mountain that he called his home. The dark beast followed, but fell into panic when it was hit from behind by a firebeam. It hadn't realized it was no longer alone. It fell even more into panic, when Thassalin slowed down and then flung his tail against its head, and it veered off course.
Knurrend and snarling it flew upwards and spat into the air. Everything became suddenly dark, as if the monster was sucking the light out of the sky and replacing it with a cloud of eternal night.
As he suddenly couldn't see anything anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself rubbing against the treetops before finally tumbling into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen, and shot straight at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!", Tenuk screamed, as he slid out of the cloud and began to circle, peering into the darkness below for Nyssi and Thassalin. "What are we supposed to do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers were already starting to work. Unfortunately, this didn't apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that hadn't collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made a great effort to get closer to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters in front of her. Everything was pitch-black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in that shadow, something screamed and shrieked.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed onto the ground beside Nyssi, sending her tumbling. But she realized the tail was only wildly flailing about and not trying to hit her specifically. The beast, or the little that Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, struck the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot crashed through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and remained motionless. The darkness surrounding it dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, holding his rifle heavily.
“That was probably... The craziest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...”, Kayel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But while he was still speaking, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them because most people found them unsettling and quite intimidating. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could use these powers in any type of darkness. And as Kayel was behaving, he seemed to be quite surprised.
“Are you okay?”, it burst out of Nyssi.
“Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, I'll be okay in a moment.” Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and regained his normal Spast form.
Now that the beast had stopped moving, they could see what it was. Its skin was jet-black and slimy, but the slime adhered tightly to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what in the world they were looking at, something shrieked and sprang out of a nearby bush. However, it did not reach them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi did not want to take any risks. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without hesitation at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
“Oops…”, Retvik murmured from the driver's seat before he clumsily turned off the engine and got out of the truck. "Ah, I wasn't aiming for that. Are you all okay?"
“You missed the whole action,” Tenuk complained. “Where were you?”
“You just left me standing there. I came as quickly as I could…”, Retvik sighed. “May I ask, what are these terrifying creatures?”
Fortunately, Retvik's question was answered by Thassalin, who had picked himself up. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not too severely injured.
“YOU'VE KILLED THE CORRUPTED ONES! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WENT AWAY AS THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS.”
“You mean the terrifying God-Monster beings that we... helped to kill?”, stuttered Tenuk.
“YES. EXACTLY THAT. THERE MIGHT BE MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT AT THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A RIFLE. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, ISN'T IT?” Thassalin limped over to Kayel and patted him on the head. “THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO CAPABLE OF KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES.”
“Uh... thanks... I think...”, shrugged Kayel with his shoulders. “So, are we done here?”
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the beasts that were now definitely dead. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the adorned Death God dagger, and began to saw off one of the horns of the beast. Afterwards, she started on the second one. But as soon as Nyssi finished, the beasts suddenly caught fire and transformed into a heap of ash in a matter of seconds. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
„So, that's both practical and impractical at the same time…“, Nyssi sighed. „But I at least got the photos, hopefully.“
